Website Compromise Investigation
Project Overview
This project involved investigating a website compromise affecting the cooking website yummyrecipesforme.com. The objective was to analyze network traffic, identify the attack method, document the incident, and recommend security improvements.

Scenario Summary
A former employee gained unauthorized access to the website’s administrative account through a brute force attack. After accessing the admin panel, the attacker modified the website source code and inserted malicious JavaScript that prompted visitors to download an executable file.
When users executed the file, they were redirected from the legitimate website to a malicious website that contained malware.

Investigation Findings
* Identified evidence of a brute force attack against the administrator account.
* Confirmed that the administrator password remained set to a default password.
* Detected unauthorized JavaScript embedded in the website source code.
* Observed DNS requests and HTTP traffic associated with the malicious redirection.
* Verified that visitors were redirected from the legitimate website to a malicious website hosting malware.

Network Protocols Identified
* DNS (Domain Name System)
* HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol)

Impact
* Unauthorized modification of website content.
* Malware distribution to website visitors.
* Loss of administrative account access.
* Increased security risk for customers and the organization.

Recommendation
Implement Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) for administrative accounts to reduce the risk of unauthorized access through brute force attacks.
